Good question ğŸ‘ Letâ€™s break Inversion of Control (IoC) in Spring Boot (Java) into very simple terms with a real-time example.

ğŸ”¹ What is Inversion of Control (IoC)?
Normally in Java, you create and control objects in your code using new.
ğŸ‘‰ With IoC, you donâ€™t control object creation. Instead, Spring Framework takes the control and injects objects where needed.

This is done using the IoC Container (like ApplicationContext in Spring).

So:

Without IoC â†’ You create objects yourself.

With IoC â†’ Spring creates objects for you and wires dependencies.

ğŸ”¹ Real-Life Example
Imagine youâ€™re watching a movie at home:

Without IoC: You need to buy a TV, DVD player, sound system, remote, and set them up yourself.

With IoC: You go to a movie theater. The theater (like Spring IoC Container) already has the screen, sound, projector. You just sit and enjoy.

ğŸ‘‰ You donâ€™t control setup â€” the theater controls everything. Thatâ€™s IoC.

ğŸ”¹ Java Example Without IoC
class Engine {
    void start() {
        System.out.println("Engine started...");
    }
}

class Car {
    private Engine engine;

    // Car creates its own engine
    public Car() {
        this.engine = new Engine();
    }

    public void drive() {
        engine.start();
        System.out.println("Car is driving...");
    }
}

public class WithoutIoC {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Car car = new Car(); // We create objects manually
        car.drive();
    }
}
Problem:
Car is tightly coupled with Engine (creates it directly).

If we want a PetrolEngine or DieselEngine, we must change the Car class.

ğŸ”¹ Java Example With IoC (Spring Boot Style)
import org.springframework.stereotype.Component;
import org.springframework.beans.factory.annotation.Autowired;
import org.springframework.boot.CommandLineRunner;
import org.springframework.boot.SpringApplication;
import org.springframework.boot.autoconfigure.SpringBootApplication;

// Dependency
@Component
class Engine {
    void start() {
        System.out.println("Engine started...");
    }
}

// Dependent
@Component
class Car {
    private Engine engine;

    @Autowired  // Spring injects Engine here
    public Car(Engine engine) {
        this.engine = engine;
    }

    public void drive() {
        engine.start();
        System.out.println("Car is driving...");
    }
}

@SpringBootApplication
public class IoCExample implements CommandLineRunner {

    private final Car car;

    @Autowired
    public IoCExample(Car car) {
        this.car = car;
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        SpringApplication.run(IoCExample.class, args);
    }

    @Override
    public void run(String... args) {
        car.drive(); // Car and Engine are injected by Spring IoC container
    }
}
ğŸ”¹ What happened here?
We didnâ€™t create new Engine() or new Car() anywhere.

Spring Bootâ€™s IoC Container created objects (Beans) and injected them automatically.

If tomorrow you replace Engine with DieselEngine, no changes in Car â€” just update the bean.

âœ… In simple words:
IoC means you donâ€™t create and manage objects yourself. Spring does it for you and wires them together.

